  "prompt": "How did Oliver Sykes damaged his voice exactly?",
  "response": "Oliver Sykes, the lead vocalist of the British rock band Bring Me the Horizon, has experienced vocal issues related to his singing style, which heavily incorporates harsh vocals such as screaming and growling. Over the years, the extensive use of these intense vocal techniques put significant strain on his vocal cords.\n\n**Vocal Strain and Damage:**\nSykes's aggressive vocal style demands a great deal from his vocal cords, leading to inflammation, nodules, and nerve damage over time. These are common issues faced by singers who engage in extreme vocal techniques without adequate vocal training or proper technique to mitigate strain.\n\n**Surgery and Recovery:**\nIn late 2018, Sykes underwent vocal cord surgery to address the damage he had sustained. The procedure was necessary to repair the affected areas of his vocal cords and to prevent further deterioration of his voice. Post-surgery, Sykes took a hiatus from performing to allow his vocal cords to heal properly.\n\n**Impact on Performances:**\nFollowing the surgery, Sykes notably adjusted his vocal approach to reduce strain and prevent re-injury. This included altering his screaming technique and focusing more on melody in his performances. The adjustments not only aided in his recovery but also influenced the musical direction of Bring Me the Horizon in subsequent releases.\n\n**Ongoing Vocal Care:**\nSince his surgery, Sykes has emphasized the importance of vocal health, incorporating techniques such as proper warm-ups, hydration, and vocal rest into his routine. By adopting these practices, he aims to maintain his vocal abilities while continuing to deliver the powerful performances that characterize his music.\n\n**Conclusion:**\nOliver Sykes's vocal damage was primarily caused by the rigorous demands of his harsh vocal style. The necessary surgical intervention and subsequent changes to his vocal technique underscore the importance of vocal health, especially for artists employing extreme singing methods. His experience serves as a reminder of the physical toll that certain vocal styles can take and the need for proper care and technique in maintaining vocal longevity.",
